  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      In critical illness, patients are highly stressed and should have elevated cortisol (stress
      hormone) secretion to adapt to stress. Dysfunction of this system is referred to as critical
      illness-related corticosteroid insufficiency. Free cortisol (unbound form) which is mainly
      responsible for its physiologic function is difficult to measure. We hypothesized that the
      salivary cortisol, which can be obtained by noninvasive methods, can more accurately
      evaluate adrenal function of critically ill patients.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
